        &nbsp;<a href="post.asp?method=ReplyQuote&amp;REPLY_ID=40957&amp;TOPIC_ID=5088&amp;FORUM_ID=2&amp;CAT_ID=1&amp;Forum_Title=General+Discussions&amp;Topic_Title=Hate+management+with+FD&amp;M="><img src="icon_reply_topic.gif" height="15" width="15" alt="Reply with Quote" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>

        <hr noshade size="2" color="#545A7D">
        
         Some things I hold as facts about FD.</P><P>1.) FD if successful removes a set amount of hate points from the hate list. This may or may not lower it enough from one successful FD to let you sit and med, depends on how much you have built vs. others engaging the mob. To try this, land a few dots on AoW, Cursed, etc. then try to sit. Now land a few dots, FD, stand up immediately then sit. The second time you will not get summoned.</P><P>2.) When you FD after aggroing a mob, if it hit you or you have landed spells on it it will usually hang around a sec before returning to what it was doing.</P><P>3.)When you FD after aggroing a mob, if it was a roamer you will always be on it's aggro list until it dies or you leave the zone (or camp or /q out).</P><P>4.) When a wanderer roams far enough that your proximity aggro is wiped you can sometimes get away with standing and running around. Your proximity aggro range with that mob however is now wider range than normal since you are on it's hate list.</P><P>5.) When you FD after aggroing a mob, if it is a static spawn or has "set rest points" on it's roaming path you will almost always be removed (95%) from the hate list and no longer have aggro after it returns and is standing for a few seconds.</P><P>6.) There are a few mobs that will always see through FD if you have done damage to them. The AoW and skelletons in the basement in Snake Temple in in The Grey (screw Verant eternally for timesinks) is a prime example of this. It doesn't matter if you have a pet up or not, they see you.<a href="#top"><img src="icon_go_up.gif" height="15" width="15" border="0" align="right" alt="Go to Top of Page"></a></font></td>
      </tr>

